               <msContents>
                  <summary>Timurid-era poet and mystic <persName xml:lang="en" key="person_90042997"
                        >‘Abd al-Raḥman Jāmī (1414–1419)</persName> composed his <title
                        xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" key="work_20616">Nafaḥāt al-'Uns min Haz̤arāt
                        al-Quds</title> (Breaths of Fellowship of Holy Gentlemen) in <placeName
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7002243" key="place_7002243"
                        >Herat</placeName> between <date calendar="#Gregorian" from="1476" to="1479"
                        >1476 and 1479</date>. Completed at the request of his friend and patron Mīr
                     ʿAlī S̲h̲īr Navā'ī, he documents the lives of 567 mystics, mostly in
                     chronological order. He both compiles and reworks the language of earlier
                     biographical accounts and also recounts figures of the late medieval period,
                     immediately prior to and during his own lifetime. Since he knew many of these
                     individuals personally—especially in his native <placeName
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7002243" key="place_7002243"
                        >Herat</placeName> and adjacent regions—scholars consider it an especially
                     valuab̦le source regarding late Timurid-era mystics and their impact upon
                     religious life and culture at that time. </summary>

                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_527-item1">
                     <author key="person_90042997" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/90042997/">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Jāmī, 1414-1492</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="ar">جامى، نور الدين عبد الرحمن‏</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_20616" change="#ids-cleanup">Nafaḥāt
                        al-Uns</title>
                     <title xml:lang="ar" key="work_20616" change="#ids-cleanup">نفحات الانس</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa" type="preface"><locus from="1b" to="1b"> برگ ۱پ (folio
                           1b):</locus> ربنا آتنا من لدیک رحمهً [رحماً] من امرنا رشداً ... </incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="fa">
                        <locus from="653a" to="653a"> برگ ۱۰۴ر (folios 653a–653b):</locus> در هشتصد
                        و هشتاد و سیوم گشت تمام * از هجرت بسر و فخر انام | </explicit>
                     <colophon>No colophon. A date of <date calendar="#Gregorian" from="1476"
                           to="1479">883 AH (1478–79 CE)</date> in the explicit pertains to
                        completion of the work by the author, not the copying of this
                        manuscript.</colophon>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                     <note>For another copy of this work held in the Rylands, see <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_26555"
                              ><idno>Persian MS 955</idno></ref>.</note>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <support>Textblock of cross-grained, externally sized and polished, ivoury
                           and buff-coloured <material>paper</material>, the latter highly flocked,
                           probably handmade in the <placeName cert="high" type="empire"
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7024418" key="place_7024418"
                              >Mughal Empire</placeName> with ~8 laid lines per cm and no
                           discernible chain lines.</support>

                        <extent><measure unit="folio" quantity="653">653 folios, nine flyeleaves
                              (ff. vii+ 653+ ii)</measure>. <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>210</height>
                              <width>125</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                              <height>117</height>
                              <width>71</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation xml:id="modern">Modern pencilled Arabic numerals added to the
                           upper-left corners of the a sides up to 55, inclusive of the original
                           endpapers, with sporadic numbering at the end.</foliation>
                        <foliation xml:id="original">Hindu- Arabic numerals added to the upper-left
                           corners of the a sides, reference for this record..</foliation>
                        <collation> Undetermined due to tight opening. <catchwords>Catchwords
                              throughout most of the lower-left corners of the b
                           sides.</catchwords></collation>
                        <condition>Handle text with caution. In fair condition, with moderate water
                           and insect damage and historical repairs throughout.</condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1 2" ruledLines="15" n="mistara"> Written in 1 to 2 columns
                           with 15 lines per page. Ruled with a <hi rend="italic">misṭarah</hi> hand
                           guide.</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="nasta_liq" medium="ink"> Written in clear
                           <material>black</material>, partially dotted nasta‘līq script with
                           <material>red</material> subheaders and markings.</handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <additions><lb/>
                     <label>Table of Contents:</label> The <locus from="iiib" to="viia">third right
                        flyleaf b side to seventh a side (ff. iiib–viia)</locus> details entries by name.<lb/>
                     <label>Marginalia:</label> Notes written in various hands througout. <lb/>
                     <label>Inscriptions:</label> The <locus from="iia" to="iia">second right
                        flyleaf a side (f. iia)</locus> bears the title of the work and the date of
                     completion, probably written by an unidentified assistant to bears two
                     notations by former owners or associates:<lb/>
                     <label>Top:</label> Above seal no. 1, a couplet in honour of a prior owner,
                     probably with reference to or by the person <q>‘Ārif</q> named in the seal:<lb/>
                     <q xml:lang="fa">آه این شهید کیست که خونش زمان زمان * خیز در خاک و قدم حجر او
                        قند.</q><lb/>
                     <label>Bottom:</label>Above seal no. 2, an acquisition statement by <persName
                        role="fmo seal ins">Mīr Taqī ‘Alī Fidvī</persName> in <placeName
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001493" key="place_7001493">Akbarābād
                        (Agra)</placeName>, partially dated <q xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">17 Ṣafar</q>,
                     with the year obscured by repairs or omitted:<lb/>
                     <q xml:lang="fa">بتاریخ هفدهم شهر صفر ختم (؟) اجزا و انظف شد بوقت (؟) در
                        اکبرآباد اتباع شد </q><lb/>
                     <label>Bookplates:</label>
                     <locus from="Inner_back_cover" to="Inner_back_cover">Left pastedown</locus>: <q
                        xml:lang="en">Bibliotheca Lindesiana</q> with pencilled shelfmark <q
                        xml:lang="en">1/J</q>, and <q xml:lang="en"><hi rend="strikethrough"
                           >Hamilton</hi> MSS No. <hi rend="strikethrough">444</hi></q>, with the
                     name and number crossed out and <q xml:lang="en">Persian</q> and <q
                        xml:lang="en">527</q> written aside. </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1950" notAfter="1990">
                        <p>Probably rebound for the <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands Library</orgName>
                           in circa <date calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1970" notAfter="1990"
                              >late 20th century CE</date> in an Islamic-style binding with flap
                           (Type II binding per Déroche).</p>
                        <p>Resewn at two stations, unsupported, with machine-made cross-grained laid
                           endpapers added to the begining and end. Original chevron endbands twined
                           in yellow and red threads replaced and stiched upon the spine, then lined
                           with cloth. New case binding with fore-edge and pentagonal envelope flap
                           constructed from pasteboards, covered in reddish-brown goatskin
                              <material>leather</material> with the edges of the boards hemmed in
                           leather along the edges, with block-printed 19th-century decorated paper
                           facing the boards.</p>
                        <decoNote type="binding">Board and flap margins blind tooled with single
                           fillet lines, twice on the flap with fleurons above the mitred corners,
                           the latter also evident underneath the decorated paper facing the
                           boards.</decoNote>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height>245</height>
                              <width>111</width>
                              <depth>95</depth>
                           </dimensions></p>
                        <condition>Binding in good condition.</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <sealDesc>
